than
on
Harriet's
more
anxious
that
she
should
escape
the
infection,
than
that
there
should
be
no
infection
in
the
complaint.
He
began
with
great
earnestness
to
entreat
her
to
refrain
from
visiting
the
sick
chamber
again,
for
the
present
to
entreat
her
to
promise
him
not
to
venture
into
such
hazard
till
he
had
seen
Mr.
Perry
and
learnt
his
opinion;
and
though
she
tried
to
laugh
it
off
and
bring
the
subject
back
into
its
proper
course,
there
was
no
putting
an
end
to
his
extreme
solicitude
about
her.
She
was
vexed.
It
did
appear
there
was
no
concealing
it
exactly
like
the
pretence
of
being
in
love
with
her,
instead
