the
most
contemptible
and
abominable!
and
she
had
difficulty
in
behaving
with
temper.
He
turned
to
Mrs.
Weston
to
implore
her
assistance,
"Would
not
she
give
him
her
support?
would
not
she
add
her
persuasions
to
his,
to
induce
Miss
Woodhouse
not
to
go
to
Mrs.
Goddard's
till
it
were
certain
that
Miss
Smith's
disorder
had
no
infection?
He
could
not
be
satisfied
without
a
promise
would
not
she
give
him
her
influence
in
procuring
it?"
"So
scrupulous
for
others,"
he
continued,
"and
yet
so
careless
for
herself!
She
wanted
me
to
nurse
